lty if they are asked to recall information from the past.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"QGnXYR4Mkd"}],"key":"nMeDw2Jej6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Experiments","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"I5cQ8RQ7kE"}],"key":"AoivNDnakn"},{"type":"text","value":" allow researchers to take control of lurking variables by ","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"uVhmsTLDJB"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"randomized assignment to treatments","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"f6a8uJqFag"}],"key":"u9rG14d0v4"},{"type":"text","value":", which helps provide more convincing evidence of causation. The design may be enhanced by making sure that subjects and/or researchers are ","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"kUmnCWODfg"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"blind","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"NmxG44g80C"}],"key":"iWolz0L9Ht"},{"type":"text","value":" to who receives what treatment. Depending on what relationship is being researched, it may be difficult to design an experiment whose setting is realistic enough that we can safely generalize the conclusions to real life.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"dq31wDhlQr"}],"key":"jLhsfO7C6a"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Another reason that observational studies are utilized rather than experiments is that certain explanatory variables—such as income or alcohol intake—either cannot or should not be controlled by researchers.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"PpNkoBd1T6"}],"key":"XsR3gOauMq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Sample surveys","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"YfJvvqaOsA"}],"key":"c91yxOROro"},{"type":"text","value":" are occasionally used to examine relationships, but often they assess values of many separate variables, such as respondents’ ","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"OaK9Sa7Aka"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"opinions","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"pHvGbv7cVl"}],"key":"MZIowTQ49r"},{"type":"text","value":" on various matters. Survey questions should be designed carefully, in order to ensure unbiased assessment of the variables’ values.","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"Yq7PXeFkcQ"}],"key":"u8Fd7SYzU9"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Throughout this unit, we established guidelines for the ideal production of data, which should be held as standards to strive for. Realistically, however, it is rarely possible to carry out a study which is completely free of flaws. Therefore, common sense must frequently be applied in order to decide which imperfections we can live with, and which ones could completely undermine a study’s results.","position":{"start":{"